                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3738: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-02-21T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1922—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. With reference to Department’s telegram No. 337 of December 22, 1921.<note
                        n="61" xml:id="d581fn61">
                        <ref target="frus1921v01#pg_385">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 385</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Advise Chinese Foreign Office that the Department and the Continental and
                    Commercial Trust and Savings Bank of Chicago continue to receive letters from
                    American purchasers of Chinese bonds issued in connection with the Continental
                    Bank loan, now in default, asking when payment of principal will be made by the
                    Chinese Government. You may state that the Department would like to receive some
                    intimation as to when these American holders of Chinese bonds may expect payment
                    now long past due.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
